rough calcium channel blockade","Blocks endothelin receptors to reduce vasoconstriction","Stimulates nitric oxide production","Increases endothelin degradation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of endothelin receptor antagonists involves \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking endothelin receptors to reduce vasoconstriction\u003C/strong\u003E. These drugs competitively block the binding of endothelin-1 to its receptors (ETA and ETB), preventing vasoconstriction and vascular smooth muscle proliferation.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting endothelin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E would theoretically reduce vasoconstriction, endothelin antagonists work by preventing the action of already produced endothelin rather than affecting its production. \u003Cstrong\u003EPromoting vasodilation through calcium channel blockade\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of calcium channel blockers, which work through an entirely different pathway. Although \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulating nitric oxide production\u003C/strong\u003E would cause vasodilation, endothelin antagonists do not interact with the nitric oxide pathway. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing endothelin degradation\u003C/strong\u003E would reduce endothelin levels, but these drugs do not affect endothelin metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EExamples of endothelin receptor antagonists include bosentan and ambrisentan. By blocking the effects of endothelin-1, these medications help reduce pulmonary vascular resistance and improve symptoms in patients with pulmonary arterial hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endothelin-1 is a potent vasoconstrictor that contributes to pulmonary arterial hypertension.","Endothelin receptor antagonists block endothelin-1 binding to ETA and ETB receptors, reducing vasoconstriction.","Endothelin receptor antagonists are used in the treatment of pulmonary arterial hypertension."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51402"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16494"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51402"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-28T09:27:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T10:24:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9185"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65953"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":